\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Baton Rouge, LA
\par 14-15 April
\par 
\par 
\par John Laudun
\par }{\fs36 Necessary Dichotomies: 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \i\fs36\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The Trope of Twinness in Folkloristics
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {I was recently asked to represent folklore, as a discipline, at the American Comparative Literature Association\rquote s annual meeting, which was 
this year held at Yale University. 
\par Writing in 1953, Merle Curti, in his }{\i American Scholarship in the Twentieth Century}{, observed that in the previous two decades \'93scholars, in thinking of knowledge as a whole, [had] reacted against its narrow compartmentalization\'94
 (4). The pull of interdisciplinarity has clearly been around for some time, and yet we seem only a little closer after at least sixty years, if Curti\rquote s history is correct, to establishing what the \'93inter\'94
 of interdisciplinarity means let alone how
 to act upon it and evaluate its successful practice. I am, then, grateful for the rather suggestive frame that Professors Silver and Wu have offered us in their notion of a metaphoric through which a discipline imagines itself. My goal in this short time
 
I have to contribute to the work of this seminar is to use that idea to explore my own home, the discipline of folklore studies, which has, for better or worse, clung to images of itself as betwixt and between in the same way that it often imagines its su
bjects and objects of study as caught in the slippery realm between past and present. Let me be clear, I am not here to champion folklore studies as the interdisciplinary paradigm }{\i par excellence}{
 nor am I here to make a straw man of it so that we may burn it and rise triumphantly from its ashes. 
\par What I would like to offer is a history of a discipline which has always understood itself as split, bifurcated into opposing forces that are locked in a struggle for the heart of the discipline. The antinomizing ten
sions that characterize so much of folkloristic discourse are both enormously beneficial to the imaginative possibilities within the discipline and frighteningly paralyzing at times. My original title for this essay was taken from the folksong, \'93
Take This Hammer,\'94
 to suggest that folklorists have been at the interdisciplinary game for a long time and that, at least one of us, has had enough of the pounding and is more than willing to let any discipline that so chooses take a good whack at lining a smooth ro
ad to the promised land that is interdisciplinarity. 
\par By \'93The Discipline Which Is Not One\'94 I hope to focus our thinking today and over the next few days on the plight of a discipline which has, first, always had to span, as evidenced by the employment of i
ts practitioners and by the professional outlets to which they had access, disciplinary grounds that were more firmly rooted in the budget lines of university departments; and, second, a discipline which has come to see itself as necessarily split. That i
s, its twinness is fundamental to the way its practitioners imagine it such that with the demise, for any number of reasons, of one cleft, another one arises to take its place. Twinness is folklore\rquote s metaphoric.
\par Perhaps the most immediate illustration of folklore\rquote 
s twinned nature can be seen in the practice of the American Folklore Society (AFS) alternately holding its meetings in conjunction with either the Modern Language Association (MLA) or the American Anthropological Association (AAA), a practice which
 began in the nineteen-forties and did not subside until late in the nineteen-sixties. This practice was the direct result of a special council meeting which produced a policy statement that leapt straight to the heart of the matter when it declared:

\par }\pard\plain \s17\ql \li720\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {It is
 clear that the major difficulty facing the Society arises from a failure to assess the importance of the fact that, by its very nature, the Society and its Journal [the }{\i Journal of American Folklore}{ (JAF)] are peripheral to two major concerns
\emdash those of anthropologists and those of persons in the humanities.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {What followed was a list of thirteen specific recommendations to implement the statement\rquote 
s suggestion that \'93the society should recognize more explicitly the points of convergence between the two fields.\'94 The recommendations laid the foundation for a reorientation of the AFS.}{\cs27\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs27\super \chftn }{ The history of the division between literary and
 anthropological folklorists is not a new one, and it owes much to the work of those who have contributed to the chronicle: McNeil (1980), Dwyer-Schick (1979), Bronner (1986), and Zumwalt (1988). I am particularly indebted, as cognizant readers will note,
 to Zumwalt\rquote s treatment; however, my overarching point remains that, Zumwalt\rquote s fine history notwithstanding, folklorists have imagined and continue to imagine the discipline as essentially split.}}}{
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
One of the very first recommendations was a stricter return to a 1914 resolution that the presidency of the society rotate between the two fields. Another was the parallel alternation
 between joint meetings with the AAA and then with the MLA. Yet another was the limitation of any editorship to five years, with the journal itself, as a central focus of the society, having its mission broadened to include both \'93theoretical papers\'94
 that h
ad previously been disdained and information helpful to amateurs. Such a set of recommendations reveals both the historical depth of the split between literary and anthropological folklorists as well as shades of a split to come between public and academi
c folklorists.
\par Starting with the founding of the American Folklore Society and the subsequent start of its publication the }{\i Journal of American Folklore}{, it is interesting to track the various figurations of the split around which the discipline operated. Wi
lliam Wells Newell, the journal\rquote s first editor and XXXX, fought to define folklore broadly and inclusively over and against the more European-influenced (read literary) notions of folklore belonging to \'93
races in which isolated tribes have been amalgamated into something resembling a nation\'94 (1890:135). He and Franz Boas were especially concerned with the \'93extravagant pretensions and loose theorizing\'94
 in the studies of popular tradition that literary folklorists, they felt, sometimes engaged in (Newell 1892:239). Newell and Boas\rquote 
s concern was over professionalism. When offered the opportunity by Fletcher Bassett of the Chicago Folklore Society to participate in the International Folklore Congress at the Columbian Exposition held in Chicago in 1892, they declined because \'93
The congress is classed among the literary congresses\'85. The American Folk-Lore Society has always considered folk-lore to belong to anthropological science.\'94 The association of folklore with literature was seen as a threat to the scientific cr
edibility of folklore studies, which the anthropological folklorists saw not as a discipline in its own right but as a subfield of the emerging discipline of anthropology.}{\cs27\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs27\super \chftn }{ It is interesting to note that not only does folklore enjoy
 the first public definition before culture, 1846 (Thoms) and 18XX (Tylor),  but that the American Folklore Society was founded before the American Anthropological Association, 1888 and 1901 respectively. For sake of comparison on metaphors of contaminati
on applied to literature, I offer up the following vignette from Bronislaw Malinowski\rquote s }{\i A Diary in the Strictest Sense of the Word}{:}}}{ Scholarship like Bassett\rquote s own }{\i Sea Phantoms: Or Legends and Superstitions of Sea an
d of Sailors}{ which engaged in \'93experimental comparison\'94 and claimed, without in all fairness to Newell and Boas, that \'93most myths of antiquity originated from speculations about natural phenomena\'94
 without any real evidence to speak of, would have contaminated anthropological folklorists investigating similar matters by sheer association.}{\cs27\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain 
\s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs27\super \chftn }{
 For sake of comparison on metaphors of contamination applied to literature, I offer up the following vignette from Bronislaw Malinowski\rquote s }{\i A Diary in the Strictest Sense of the Word}{:}}}{
\par In order to ward off the danger, Newell and Boas adopted a more strict editorial policy for the journal, one which eschewed \'93philosophic speculation\'94 about the origin of myths and customs and encouraged collection among the \'93primitive races.\'94
 The former was described as \'93theoretic discussion\'94 and the latter as \'93practical research.\'94 This stricter policy, in fact, undermined Newell\rquote s own earlier preference for alternating issues of the journal, \'93one on Indian lore\'94 and 
\'93one on English, French, etc.\'94 Indeed, it wasn\rquote t long before Boas and others came to be known as \'93the Indian men.\'94
\par As a number of observers (Zumwalt, Dwyer-Schick) have pointed out, much of the battle focused on
 the editorship of the journal. When Newell died in 1907, it was not long afterwards that a few members began to correspond with each other and later with Boas about a possible broadening of the journal\rquote s purview to include the \'93
literary side of folklore.\'94
 The effort was undertaken under the auspices of expanding the membership of the society, and thus increasing revenues to offset the printing costs of the journal. It was hoped that such a move would not only welcome new members but also bring back into t
h
e fold individuals like George Kittredge, who like his teacher Francis Child as well as Joel Chandler Harris, and Mark Twain had been a founding member of the society, but who, under the narrow anthropological editorial regime spearheaded by Newell and su
pported by Boas, had sought out other avenues for discussion and publication.
\par Boas himself understood the split as being between European and anthropological folklorists, and in his response to Alfred Tozzer, who was the one who came to him with the suggested change of course, he worried that:
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {
The groups of people interested in the study of European folk-lore differ so much in their general points of view and their other interests from our people, that the \'93Folk-Lore Journal\'94 might become very heterogeneous 
unless we happen to interest strongly a number of men who are at the same time imbued with the anthropological spirit. (qtd. in Zumwalt 35)
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {Tozzer himself figured the split a bit differently, noting that it was his wish \'93to give more prominence to the lite
rary side of folk-lore in the Journal so that the interest will not be confined strictly to the aboriginal side.\'94
\par }\pard\plain \s16\ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Tozzer\rquote s complaint is born out in the dominance of the Society\rquote 
s presidency by anthropologists: in its first twenty-six years, only six litera
ry folklorists held the office for a total of nine years. The situation was already exacerbated when at the 1914 meeting it was resolved to alternate annually the presidents between the two sides \'93as far as possible.\'94
 Over the next twenty-six years, howeve
r, only four folklorists with a literary orientation would become president, again for a total of nine years. The net result was that the literary folklorists simply began to stay away from the Society, as one of George Kittredge\rquote 
s students, Stith Thompson, noted in his memoirs. The split, then, was well entrenched and figured across a number of dimensions. When the literary folklorists ventured out into the field, and a number of them like John Lomax and Alc\'e9
e Fortier did, it was to collect folklore from w
hat would have been a peasant population in order to classify it into genres like the ballad (Child, Kittredge), the folktale (Thompson), or the proverb (Archer Taylor). They operated with written literature in the background and the library was never far
 
from view. Anthropological folklorists, on the other hand, felt a keen obligation to get out into the field in order to collect and document the non-Western, tribal cultures of groups like the American Indians in order to understand either the history of 
c
ertain cultural traits (Boas) or to understand cultural patterns (Ruth Benedict). Their focus was on particular cultures with the idea that culture is a universal phenomenon always in the background. When both managed to come together, as in the case of A
frican American folklore, they sought different things: European elements for the literary folklorists and African elements for the anthropological folklorists.
\par The part-time, only half-intended exile of the literary folklorists from the Society did not nec
essarily preclude them from practicing within the discipline; they simply sought out other venues, one of which was the Modern Language Association meetings, which in their first few years were small enough that folklorists mingled among the general popul
a
tion easily. In 1921, the MLA had grown enough that it sponsored its first collection of groups, one of which was the Popular Literature group which was part of the general division of Comparative literature. In 1931, the Popular Literature group stated i
n its annual report that \'93a course in folklore may well form a part of any of the Language or Literature departments or of that of Anthropology. It should act as a valuable liaison between departments.\'94
 Eventually, the conception of Popular Literature, which the members of the group had used in the same sense as \'93popular antiquities\'94
 had once been used to designate folklore or what we now sometimes call oral literature, shifted in the 1960s to the popular literature of the mystery, western, detective, or romance novel. 
\par By then, the literary folklorists, who had started out with Francis Child and later George Kittredge at Harvard, had gained enough ground at universities throughout the country that it was easy to repopulate the American Folklore Society and s
hape it to fit more closely their vision of the discipline. Indeed, in a war of words that broke out in the fifties, it was the literary folklorists who grabbed the folklore standard, making adept rhetorical moves that managed to exile anthropologists fro
m the discipline. In his defense of the myth-ritual theory, Stanley Hyman dismissed William Bascom by noting that: \'93Bascom cannot debate Greek drama \'85 or New Testament myth \'85 or medieval romance \'85 or Homeric epic \'85
 he is not informed on such matters; he is an anthropologist, not a folklorist.\'94 
\par Richard Dorson, who was the longtime chair of the Indiana University Folklore Institute, my own alma mater, made similar accusations as the debate over the origins of traits and motifs found in African American folklo
re continued through the ninetten-fifties and into the sixties. He accused anthropologists of usurping folklorists in the founding of the American Folklore Society, and then accused the former of losing interest in folklore and withdrawing to studies of s
o
cial organization or personality and culture. His figuration of the split was that it was between anthropological and American folklorists. Within such a scheme, anthropologists are not only no longer a part of the society, they are no longer part of the 
nation.
\par By the mid-nineteen-sixties, however, with the wide dispersal of structuralism across the American academic landscape and the appearance of such works as Vladimir Propp\rquote s }{\i The Morphology of the Folktale}{ in 1958 or Claude L\'e9vi-Strauss
\rquote s own contribution to the special issue of the }{\i Journal of American Folklore}{ on myth, it had become apparent that there the great divide between the two denominations was not as great as it once seemed.}{\cs27\super \chftn {\footnote\ftnalt 
\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs27\super \chftn }{ This did not, however, prevent Michael Bell from depicting anthropology\rquote 
s understanding of folklore as its \'93handmaiden,\'94 nor William McNeil from referring to the Boasian era as a \'93strangehold.\'94}}}{ Inspired by the social changes happening all around them and heartene
d by thinkers like the linguist Dell Hymes who reversed structuralist linguistics\rquote 
 obsession with competence in order to focus on the actual use of language in the context of particular situation, a number of folklorists saw an opportunity to elaborate the
 great typologies, with their manifold categories, with a much finer understanding of the uses of tales, proverbs, and riddles, which would come from careful ethnographic description. 
\par The ethnography of speaking would seem to offer the possibility of giving everyone a place a the table, but it wasn\rquote t long before the twinning imagination of the discipline erupted into a debate which boiled things down to text and context.
\par Not long after performance theory made its formal debut in the pages of the }{\i Journal of American Folklore}{, TEXT/CONTEXT.
\par Academic/public.
\par Folklore/not folklore. Bauman: \'93folklore as an autonomous discipline is counter-productive\'94 (1996: 15).
\par Disciplined interdisciplinarity is an El Dorado. Whether the end result is a trope or a metaphoric as
 I have outlined here or the more articulated paradigm that Thomas Kuhn explored in the sciences over thirty years ago, certain parts of the process would seem inevitable, one of which must certainly be the development of a culture which by definition and
 
necessity must exclude certain ideas from consideration. Interdisciplinarity, in this light, can be considered another form of transcendence, a desire to escape the boundaries of our own thinking. That that is not likely to happen is something history has
 made mostly clear. That we continue to desire it in the face of its unattainability is to our credit.
